{
  "Which phylum do sponges belong to?": "",
  "Porifera": "",
  "Cnidaria": "",
  "Arthropoda": "",
  "Mollusca": "",
  "Sponges are classified under Phylum Porifera, which means 'pore-bearing.' Their bodies are covered in tiny pores that allow water to flow through for feeding and gas exchange.": "",
  "How do sponges primarily obtain their food?": "",
  "They absorb nutrients through their outer skin": "",
  "They photosynthesize using chloroplasts": "",
  "They actively hunt small prey": "",
  "They filter particles from water passing through their bodies": "",
  "Sponges are filter feeders. They draw water through their porous bodies using specialized cells called choanocytes, which trap bacteria and tiny food particles from the water current.": "",
  "What type of symmetry do jellyfish and other cnidarians display?": "",
  "Pentaradial symmetry": "",
  "Asymmetry": "",
  "Radial symmetry": "",
  "Bilateral symmetry": "",
  "Cnidarians exhibit radial symmetry, meaning their body parts are arranged around a central axis like spokes on a wheel. This allows them to detect and respond to the environment from all directions equally.": "",
  "Which of the following organisms is a cnidarian?": "",
  "Sea urchin": "",
  "Sea sponge": "",
  "Sea anemone": "",
  "Sea cucumber": "",
  "Sea anemones belong to Phylum Cnidaria along with jellyfish, corals, and hydrozoans. Sea urchins and sea cucumbers are echinoderms, and sea sponges belong to Phylum Porifera.": "",
  "What is the lifestyle of an adult sponge?": "",
  "Free-swimming": "",
  "Sessile": "",
  "Parasitic": "",
  "Migratory": "",
  "Adult sponges are sessile, meaning they are permanently attached to a surface and do not move. They spend their entire adult lives anchored to rocks, coral, or the ocean floor.": "",
  "Which two body forms alternate in many cnidarian life cycles?": "",
  "Nymph and adult": "",
  "Trochophore and veliger": "",
  "Polyp and medusa": "",
  "Larva and pupa": "",
  "Many cnidarians alternate between a sessile polyp form and a free-swimming medusa form during their life cycle. The polyp is typically tube-shaped and attached, while the medusa is bell-shaped and mobile.": "",
  "What hard structures help support the body of many sponges?": "",
  "Bones": "",
  "Scales": "",
  "Shells": "",
  "Spicules": "",
  "Spicules are tiny, needle-like structural elements made of silica or calcium carbonate that provide support and protection for sponges. They form a sort of internal skeleton that helps the sponge maintain its shape.": "",
  "What major structure do coral reefs provide in ocean ecosystems?": "",
  "Deep-sea hydrothermal vents": "",
  "Nesting grounds exclusively for sea turtles": "",
  "Habitat and shelter for a huge diversity of marine life": "",
  "Sources of freshwater for nearshore areas": "",
  "Coral reefs are often called the 'rainforests of the sea' because they support an enormous variety of marine organisms. They provide food, shelter, breeding grounds, and nursery habitat for thousands of species.": "",
  "Which cnidarian body form is typically free-swimming and bell-shaped?": "",
  "Polyp": "",
  "Planula": "",
  "Osculum": "",
  "Medusa": "",
  "The medusa form is the free-swimming, bell-shaped stage seen in jellyfish. It has tentacles hanging down from the bell and moves by pulsating contractions that propel it through the water.": "",
  "What type of relationship exists between coral and the zooxanthellae algae living inside them?": "",
  "Competition": "",
  "Mutualism": "",
  "Commensalism": "",
  "Parasitism": "",
  "Coral and zooxanthellae share a mutualistic relationship. The algae photosynthesize and provide the coral with nutrients and energy, while the coral provides the algae with shelter and access to sunlight.": "",
  "What does the term 'Porifera' literally mean?": "",
  "Pore-bearing": "",
  "Spiny skin": "",
  "Stinging cell": "",
  "Soft body": "",
  "Porifera comes from the Latin words 'porus' (pore) and 'ferre' (to bear), meaning 'pore-bearing.' This name reflects the countless tiny openings on a sponge's body through which water flows.": "",
  "What are cnidocytes?": "",
  "Photosynthetic cells found in coral tissue": "",
  "Reproductive cells produced during budding": "",
  "Specialized stinging cells unique to cnidarians": "",
  "Cells that form the hard skeleton of sponges": "",
  "Cnidocytes are specialized cells found only in cnidarians that contain a stinging organelle called a nematocyst. When triggered, the nematocyst fires a barbed thread that can inject toxins to capture prey or deter predators.": "",
  "What is a nematocyst?": "",
  "A type of larval stage in sponges": "",
  "A calcium carbonate plate found in coral skeletons": "",
  "A flexible protein that supports sponge structure": "",
  "A harpoon-like organelle inside a cnidocyte used for stinging": "",
  "A nematocyst is the stinging organelle housed within a cnidocyte. It contains a coiled, barbed thread that rapidly uncoils upon contact, piercing prey or threats and delivering venom. It is one of the fastest biological mechanisms known.": "",
  "What does 'sessile' mean in biology?": "",
  "An organism that floats freely in ocean currents": "",
  "An organism that migrates seasonally": "",
  "An organism that is permanently attached to a surface and does not move": "",
  "An organism that lives inside another organism": "",
  "Sessile describes an organism that is fixed in one place and unable to move on its own. Adult sponges, coral polyps, and barnacles are common examples of sessile marine organisms.": "",
  "What is spongin?": "",
  "A flexible protein fiber that forms the skeleton of some sponges": "",
  "A type of reproductive cell in sponges": "",
  "A pigment that gives sponges their color": "",
  "A toxin released by sponge cells for defense": "",
  "Spongin is a modified collagen protein that forms a flexible, fibrous skeleton in many sponge species. Bath sponges, for example, have skeletons made primarily of spongin, which gives them their soft and compressible texture.": "",
  "What term describes the large opening at the top of a sponge where water exits?": "",
  "Gastrovascular cavity": "",
  "Ostia": "",
  "Spongocoel": "",
  "The osculum is the large opening at the top of a sponge through which filtered water is expelled. Water enters through many tiny pores called ostia, passes through the internal cavity (spongocoel), and exits through the osculum.": "",
  "What are zooxanthellae?": "",
  "Parasitic worms that infect coral tissue": "",
  "Venomous barbs found in cnidocytes": "",
  "Symbiotic photosynthetic algae that live within coral tissue": "",
  "Larvae of jellyfish during the planula stage": "",
  "Zooxanthellae are single-celled dinoflagellate algae that live symbiotically inside coral tissue. They photosynthesize and provide up to 90% of the coral's energy needs, while also giving corals much of their vibrant color.": "",
  "What is the polyp body form in cnidarians?": "",
  "A free-swimming, bell-shaped form with trailing tentacles": "",
  "A colonial form found only in sponges": "",
  "A sessile, tube-shaped form with the mouth and tentacles facing upward": "",
  "A microscopic larval form that drifts in ocean currents": "",
  "The polyp is the sessile body form of cnidarians, shaped like a tube or cylinder with a mouth and tentacles pointing upward. Corals and sea anemones spend their adult lives in the polyp form.": "",
  "What does the term 'Cnidaria' refer to?": "",
  "The Latin word for 'jelly float'": "",
  "The Greek word for 'soft body'": "",
  "The Greek word for 'stinging nettle'": "",
  "The Latin word for 'coral builder'": "",
  "Cnidaria comes from the Greek word 'cnidos,' meaning stinging nettle. This name reflects the phylum's defining feature: cnidocytes, or stinging cells, that all members possess.": "",
  "What is coral bleaching?": "",
  "The shedding of old coral tissue to allow new growth": "",
  "The loss of symbiotic zooxanthellae from coral tissue, causing it to turn white": "",
  "A natural process where coral changes color to attract fish": "",
  "A disease caused by bacterial infection of the coral skeleton": "",
  "Coral bleaching occurs when stressed corals expel their symbiotic zooxanthellae algae, causing the coral to turn white. Common stressors include elevated water temperatures, pollution, and ocean acidification. Without the algae, coral can starve and die.": "",
  "A marine biologist observes that a reef organism is attached to a rock, has no organs or true tissues, and water flows through tiny pores in its body. What is this organism most likely?": "",
  "A sponge": "",
  "A coral polyp": "",
  "A sea anemone": "",
  "A jellyfish": "",
  "The lack of true tissues and organs, sessile attachment, and porous body are all characteristic of sponges (Phylum Porifera). Unlike cnidarians, sponges have no specialized tissue layers and rely entirely on water flow through pores for feeding.": "",
  "A diver notices that a coral reef has turned completely white after a summer of record-high ocean temperatures. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "The coral expelled its zooxanthellae due to thermal stress, causing bleaching": "",
  "A predator consumed all the coral's pigmented tissue": "",
  "New white coral species have moved in and displaced the original reef": "",
  "The coral has died and been replaced by white sand": "",
  "Elevated ocean temperatures cause coral to become stressed and expel their symbiotic zooxanthellae. Since the algae provide both nutrition and color, their loss turns the coral white—a process called coral bleaching. Prolonged bleaching can lead to coral death.": "",
  "A student is examining a preserved marine specimen and finds tiny, sharp, needle-like structures made of silica within its body. These structures most likely serve what function in which organism?": "",
  "Stinging in a jellyfish": "",
  "Digestion in a sea anemone": "",
  "Locomotion in a coral polyp": "",
  "Structural support in a sponge": "",
  "Silica-based needle-like structures are spicules, which provide structural support and protection for sponges. Different sponge species produce spicules of varying shapes and materials, including silica (glass) and calcium carbonate.": "",
  "A swimmer at the beach gets stung by a jellyfish tentacle. Which cellular structure was directly responsible for injecting venom into the swimmer's skin?": "",
  "Nematocysts within cnidocytes": "",
  "Choanocytes": "",
  "Zooxanthellae": "",
  "Nematocysts are the stinging organelles housed within cnidocytes on jellyfish tentacles. When triggered by physical contact, they rapidly discharge a barbed thread that penetrates skin and injects venom. This is how all cnidarians capture prey and defend themselves.": "",
  "Researchers discover a new deep-sea cnidarian species. In the lab, they observe it alternating between a stage that is attached to rocks and a stage that swims freely. What are these two stages called?": "",
  "Spore and gamete": "",
  "Sessile and planktonic": "",
  "Larva and adult": "",
  "The attached stage is the polyp and the free-swimming stage is the medusa. Many cnidarians exhibit this alternation of generations, with the polyp reproducing asexually and the medusa reproducing sexually.": "",
  "An aquarium wants to keep corals healthy in a display tank. Based on the mutualistic relationship between corals and zooxanthellae, which tank condition is most critical to maintain?": "",
  "High salinity above 50 ppt to mimic deep-ocean conditions": "",
  "Adequate lighting so zooxanthellae can photosynthesize": "",
  "Very cold water temperatures below 10°C": "",
  "Complete darkness to reduce algal growth": "",
  "Since zooxanthellae are photosynthetic algae that provide up to 90% of a coral's energy, adequate lighting is essential. Without sufficient light, the algae cannot photosynthesize, and the coral will be deprived of its primary energy source.": "",
  "A scientist compares two marine organisms: one has true tissues organized into two layers (ectoderm and endoderm) and possesses stinging cells, while the other lacks true tissues entirely. How should the scientist classify them?": "",
  "Both belong to Phylum Porifera": "",
  "The first is a sponge and the second is a cnidarian": "",
  "The first is a cnidarian and the second is a sponge": "",
  "Both belong to Phylum Cnidaria": "",
  "Cnidarians have two true tissue layers (ectoderm and endoderm) separated by a jelly-like mesoglea, and they possess cnidocytes for stinging. Sponges lack true tissues and organs entirely, making them the simplest multicellular animals.": "",
  "A sponge population in a polluted bay has declined sharply. Given that sponges are filter feeders, which factor most directly explains why pollution harms sponge survival?": "",
  "Pollution causes sponges to release their nematocysts": "",
  "Toxins and particles in the water are drawn into the sponge's body during filter feeding": "",
  "Polluted water prevents sponges from using radial symmetry for defense": "",
  "Pollution makes the water too warm for sponge spicules to form": "",
  "Because sponges pump large volumes of water through their bodies to filter-feed, they inevitably absorb pollutants, toxins, and excess sediment. This makes them highly vulnerable to water pollution and useful as bioindicators of water quality.": "",
  "A colony of coral polyps is observed reproducing by budding, where new polyps grow from the sides of existing ones. What type of reproduction is this, and how does it contribute to reef formation?": "",
  "Asexual reproduction; new genetically identical polyps expand the colony and build the reef structure": "",
  "Regeneration; damaged tissue heals but does not create new polyps": "",
  "Fragmentation; broken pieces drift away to start new reefs": "",
  "Sexual reproduction; it increases genetic diversity in the reef": "",
  "Budding is a form of asexual reproduction where a new organism grows from the parent. In corals, budding produces genetically identical polyps that remain connected, gradually expanding the colony and secreting calcium carbonate to build the reef framework.": "",
  "In a tide pool, a sea anemone has a clownfish living among its tentacles. The clownfish is not stung because it is coated in protective mucus. The clownfish drives away predators that would eat the anemone, and the anemone's stinging tentacles protect the clownfish. What type of ecological relationship does this represent?": "",
  "Parasitism, because the clownfish benefits at the anemone's expense": "",
  "Commensalism, because only the clownfish benefits": "",
  "Mutualism, because both the clownfish and the anemone benefit": "",
  "Competition, because both species are fighting for the same food": "",
  "This is mutualism because both organisms benefit from the relationship. The clownfish gains protection from the anemone's stinging tentacles, while the anemone is defended from predators by the territorial clownfish. Both species have higher survival rates together.": ""
}